        <profileDesc>
            <abstract>
                <p>Hagiographic texts of <persName ref="PRS10618ZaraB"/>, an Ethiopian saint from the 17th-century 
                    <placeName ref="LOC3549Gojjam"/>. The hagiographical dossier contains miracles, as well as poetic texts, but no gadl 
                    (life of the saint), unless the miracle accounts are often recounted as Gadla ʾabuna Zarʾa Buruk. The number of miracles may vary
                    from the core transmission of 26 miracles to 42 or more in other versions. The inclusion of a significantly greater number of miracles
                    may have occurred due to the merging of traditions relating to another saint with the same name. The poetic texts included in the 
                    dossier may vary as well and comprise malkǝʾ-hymns as for instance <ref type="work" corresp="LIT0512Malke"/>, salām-hymns 
                    and qǝne-poems.</p><!-- For more information and ungoing research see Issue #3192 -->
            </abstract>
